module.exports = [
  [65, "The Sharing Economy", "经济", 2,
"The sharing economy has disrupted traditional business models across numerous industries. Platforms like Uber, Airbnb, and TaskRabbit connect people who have underutilized assets or skills with those who need them, creating new economic opportunities while challenging established industries.\n\nProponents argue that the sharing economy promotes more efficient use of resources. Spare rooms, idle vehicles, and free time are transformed into income-generating assets. Consumers benefit from lower prices and greater convenience, while providers gain flexible earning opportunities.\n\nHowever, critics raise serious concerns. Workers in the gig economy often lack the protections afforded to traditional employees, including minimum wage guarantees, health insurance, and retirement benefits. The classification of workers as independent contractors rather than employees has been the subject of numerous legal battles.\n\nThe impact on traditional businesses has been significant. Taxi companies, hotels, and other established industries have struggled to compete with sharing economy platforms that operate under different regulatory frameworks. Cities around the world are grappling with how to regulate these platforms to protect consumers and workers while preserving the benefits of innovation.",
"共享经济颠覆了众多行业的传统商业模式。优步、爱彼迎等平台将拥有未充分利用资产或技能的人与需要这些的人连接起来。\n\n支持者认为共享经济促进了更高效的资源利用。空余房间、闲置车辆和空闲时间被转化为创收资产。\n\n然而，批评者提出了严重关切。零工经济中的工人通常缺乏传统员工享有的保护，包括最低工资保障、健康保险和退休福利。\n\n对传统企业的影响是显著的。出租车公司、酒店等传统行业一直在努力与在不同监管框架下运营的共享经济平台竞争。",
338,
[["What does the sharing economy do according to proponents?","Wastes resources","Promotes more efficient use of resources","Eliminates all jobs","Increases prices","B","文章指出支持者认为共享经济促进了更高效的资源利用。"],["What concern do critics raise about gig economy workers?","They earn too much money","They lack protections like minimum wage guarantees and health insurance","They have too many benefits","They work too few hours","B","文章指出零工经济工人缺乏传统员工享有的保护。"],["How are workers in the sharing economy typically classified?","As full-time employees","As independent contractors","As government workers","As company owners","B","文章指出工人被分类为独立承包商而非员工。"],["The word 'grappling' most likely means:","Ignoring completely","Struggling to deal with","Easily solving","Avoiding","B","'grappling'意为'努力应对、挣扎处理'。"]]],

  [66, "Globalization and Trade", "经济", 2,
"Globalization has transformed the world economy over the past several decades, creating unprecedented connections between countries through trade, investment, and the movement of people. International trade has grown dramatically, with the value of global merchandise exports increasing from about 300 billion dollars in 1970 to over 20 trillion dollars today.\n\nThe benefits of globalization are substantial. Consumers enjoy access to a wider variety of goods at lower prices. Developing countries have gained access to global markets, creating jobs and lifting millions out of poverty. The flow of ideas, technology, and culture across borders has accelerated innovation and human progress.\n\nHowever, globalization has also created winners and losers. Manufacturing workers in developed countries have lost jobs as production moved to countries with lower labor costs. Income inequality has increased within many nations, even as global inequality has decreased. Environmental standards may be compromised as countries compete to attract investment.\n\nThe recent rise of protectionism and trade tensions challenges the globalization model. Some countries are imposing tariffs and trade barriers, arguing that free trade has benefited corporations at the expense of workers. Finding a balance between open trade and protecting domestic interests remains one of the most challenging economic policy questions of our time.",
"全球化在过去几十年中改变了世界经济，通过贸易、投资和人员流动创造了各国之间前所未有的联系。国际贸易急剧增长，全球商品出口价值从1970年的约3000亿美元增加到今天的超过20万亿美元。\n\n全球化的好处是巨大的。消费者可以以更低的价格获得更丰富的商品。发展中国家获得了进入全球市场的机会，创造了就业机会。\n\n然而，全球化也创造了赢家和输家。发达国家的制造业工人随着生产转移到劳动力成本较低的国家而失去了工作。许多国家内部的不平等加剧了。\n\n最近保护主义和贸易紧张局势的兴起挑战了全球化模式。在开放贸易和保护国内利益之间找到平衡仍然是我们这个时代最具挑战性的经济政策问题之一。",
338,
[["What was the value of global merchandise exports in 1970?","About 30 billion dollars","About 300 billion dollars","About 3 trillion dollars","About 30 trillion dollars","B","文章指出1970年全球商品出口价值约3000亿美元。"],["What benefit of globalization is mentioned for developing countries?","They have gained access to global markets, creating jobs and reducing poverty","They have eliminated all poverty","They no longer need to trade","They have the highest wages globally","A","文章指出发展中国家获得了全球市场准入，创造了就业和减少贫困。"],["What challenge to the globalization model is mentioned?","Too much free trade","The rise of protectionism and trade tensions","Decreased international communication","Lower consumer prices","B","文章指出保护主义和贸易紧张局势的兴起挑战了全球化模式。"],["The word 'protectionism' most likely means:","Supporting free trade","Government policies that restrict international trade to protect domestic industries","Environmental protection","Consumer rights","B","'protectionism'意为'保护主义'。"]]],

  [67, "The Rise of E-commerce", "经济", 1,
"E-commerce has revolutionized the way people buy and sell goods and services. Online retail sales have grown exponentially, from virtually nothing in the 1990s to over 5 trillion dollars annually worldwide. This transformation has reshaped consumer behavior, business strategies, and the global economy.\n\nThe convenience of online shopping is a major driver of e-commerce growth. Consumers can browse and purchase products from anywhere at any time, compare prices across multiple retailers, and have items delivered directly to their doors. The COVID-19 pandemic dramatically accelerated this trend as lockdowns forced consumers to shop online.\n\nSmall businesses have both benefited from and been challenged by e-commerce. Online platforms allow small retailers to reach customers worldwide, but they also face intense competition from large online marketplaces. Independent sellers on platforms like Amazon must often compete with the platform's own products, creating an uneven playing field.\n\nThe growth of e-commerce has had significant impacts on traditional retail. Brick-and-mortar stores have closed in record numbers, and shopping malls face declining foot traffic. However, the line between online and offline retail is blurring as traditional retailers develop online presence and e-commerce companies open physical stores. The future of retail likely lies in omnichannel strategies that seamlessly integrate digital and physical shopping experiences.",
"电子商务已经彻底改变了人们买卖商品和服务的方式。在线零售额从1990年代几乎为零增长到全球每年超过5万亿美元。\n\n在线购物的便利性是电子商务增长的主要驱动力。消费者可以随时随地浏览和购买产品。新冠疫情大大加速了这一趋势。\n\n小企业既从电子商务中受益，也面临挑战。在线平台允许小型零售商接触全球客户，但它们也面临来自大型在线市场的激烈竞争。\n\n电子商务的增长对传统零售产生了重大影响。实体店以创纪录的数量关闭。然而，在线和线下零售之间的界限正在模糊。零售的未来可能在于无缝整合数字和物理购物体验的全渠道策略。",
338,
[["How much are annual global online retail sales?","Over 500 billion dollars","Over 5 trillion dollars","Over 50 trillion dollars","Over 5 billion dollars","B","文章指出全球在线零售额每年超过5万亿美元。"],["What accelerated the e-commerce trend?","The COVID-19 pandemic","Decreased internet access","Lower quality products","Government restrictions on shopping","A","文章指出新冠疫情大大加速了电子商务趋势。"],["What challenge do small businesses face on e-commerce platforms?","No challenges at all","Intense competition from large online marketplaces and the platform's own products","Too many customers","Excessive profits","B","文章指出小企业面临来自大型在线市场和平台自身产品的激烈竞争。"],["The word 'omnichannel' most likely means:","Using only one sales channel","Using all available channels seamlessly integrated together","Using only physical stores","Using only online sales","B","'omnichannel'意为'全渠道的'。"]]],

  [68, "Income Inequality", "经济", 3,
"Income inequality has become one of the defining economic issues of the twenty-first century. In many countries, the gap between the rich and the poor has widened significantly over the past several decades, raising concerns about social cohesion, economic stability, and democratic governance.\n\nThe statistics are striking. The richest 1 percent of the global population owns more wealth than the remaining 99 percent combined. In the United States, the top 10 percent of earners take home nearly half of all income, while the bottom 50 percent earns just 12 percent. This trend is not limited to developed countries; inequality has increased in most nations around the world.\n\nMultiple factors contribute to rising inequality. Technological change has increased the demand for highly skilled workers while reducing opportunities for those with less education. Globalization has shifted manufacturing jobs to lower-wage countries. Declining union membership and minimum wages that have not kept pace with inflation have also contributed.\n\nThe consequences of extreme inequality are far-reaching. It can undermine social trust, increase political polarization, and reduce economic mobility. Children born into poverty face significant disadvantages in education and career opportunities, perpetuating inequality across generations. Addressing income inequality requires comprehensive policies including progressive taxation, investment in education, strengthened social safety nets, and policies that ensure workers share in economic growth.",
"收入不平等已成为二十一世纪最重要的经济问题之一。在许多国家，过去几十年来贫富差距显著扩大。\n\n统计数据令人震惊。全球最富有的1%人口拥有的财富超过了其余99%的总和。在美国，收入最高的10%获得了近一半的收入，而底层的50%只获得12%。\n\n多种因素导致不平等加剧。技术变革增加了对高技能工人的需求，同时减少了受教育程度较低者的机会。全球化将制造业工作转移到了低工资国家。工会成员减少和最低工资未跟上通胀也起了作用。\n\n极端不平等的后果是深远的。它可能破坏社会信任，增加政治两极分化，并减少经济流动性。解决收入不平等需要包括累进税制、教育投资、加强社会安全网等全面政策。",
338,
[["What percentage of global wealth does the richest 1% own?","Less than the remaining 99%","More than the remaining 99% combined","About the same as the remaining 99%","About 10%","B","文章指出最富有的1%拥有的财富超过了其余99%的总和。"],["In the US, what percentage of income do the top 10% earn?","About 25%","About 50%","Nearly half","About 75%","C","文章指出美国收入最高的10%获得了近一半的收入。"],["What is one factor contributing to rising inequality?","Decreased technology use","Technological change increasing demand for highly skilled workers","Equal education for all","Increased union membership","B","文章指出技术变革增加了对高技能工人的需求。"],["The word 'progressive' in progressive taxation most likely means:","Regressive","Tax rates that increase as income increases","Flat rate","Voluntary","B","'progressive taxation'意为'累进税制'，即税率随收入增加而提高。"]]],

  [69, "Cryptocurrency and Digital Finance", "经济", 3,
"Cryptocurrency has emerged as one of the most disruptive innovations in the financial world. Since the creation of Bitcoin in 2009, thousands of cryptocurrencies have been launched, with a total market capitalization that has exceeded 2 trillion dollars at its peak.\n\nCryptocurrencies operate on blockchain technology, which provides a decentralized and transparent system for recording transactions. Unlike traditional currencies issued by central banks, cryptocurrencies are not controlled by any single entity. This decentralization is seen by proponents as a fundamental advantage, protecting against government manipulation and providing financial freedom.\n\nHowever, cryptocurrencies face significant challenges. Price volatility makes them unreliable as stores of value or units of account. Regulatory uncertainty varies widely across jurisdictions, creating a patchwork of rules that complicates adoption. The environmental impact of energy-intensive mining processes, particularly for Bitcoin, has drawn criticism. Security concerns including hacking, fraud, and lost passwords have resulted in billions of dollars in losses.\n\nCentral bank digital currencies, or CBDCs, represent a government response to the cryptocurrency phenomenon. Unlike decentralized cryptocurrencies, CBDCs would be issued and controlled by central banks, combining the efficiency of digital payments with the stability of government-backed currency. The evolution of digital finance will likely reshape the global financial system in profound ways in the coming decades.",
"加密货币已成为金融界最具颠覆性的创新之一。自2009年比特币创建以来，已推出数千种加密货币，总市值在巅峰时期超过2万亿美元。\n\n加密货币在区块链技术上运行，提供了一个去中心化和透明的交易记录系统。与传统货币不同，加密货币不受任何单一实体控制。\n\n然而，加密货币面临重大挑战。价格波动使其作为价值储存或记账单位不可靠。能源密集型挖矿过程的环境影响受到了批评。安全问题包括黑客攻击和欺诈造成了数十亿美元的损失。\n\n央行数字货币（CBDC）代表了政府对加密货币现象的回应。与去中心化加密货币不同，CBDC将由中央银行发行和控制。数字金融的演变可能在未来几十年以深刻的方式重塑全球金融体系。",
338,
[["When was Bitcoin created?","2005","2009","2015","2000","B","文章指出比特币于2009年创建。"],["What is the total market capitalization of cryptocurrencies at its peak?","Over 200 billion dollars","Over 2 trillion dollars","Over 20 trillion dollars","Over 200 million dollars","B","文章指出加密货币总市值在巅峰时期超过2万亿美元。"],["What are CBDCs?","Decentralized cryptocurrencies","Central bank digital currencies issued and controlled by central banks","Credit card companies","Commercial bank deposits","B","文章指出CBDC是由中央银行发行和控制的央行数字货币。"],["The word 'patchwork' most likely means:","A uniform, consistent system","An inconsistent mixture of different things","A single comprehensive law","An international treaty","B","'patchwork'意为'拼凑的东西'，指不一致的规则混合体。"]]],

  [70, "The Gig Economy", "经济", 2,
"The gig economy has transformed the nature of work for millions of people around the world. Characterized by short-term contracts, freelance work, and independent contracting rather than permanent employment, the gig economy offers both flexibility and uncertainty.\n\nRide-sharing drivers, food delivery couriers, freelance writers, and online tutors are among the millions of workers who participate in the gig economy. Digital platforms connect these workers with customers, making it easier than ever to find short-term work. For many, the flexibility to set their own hours and choose their assignments is the primary attraction.\n\nHowever, the gig economy comes with significant downsides. Workers typically lack benefits such as health insurance, paid leave, and retirement plans. Income can be unpredictable, and workers bear all the financial risk of slow periods. The absence of job security and career progression opportunities can create long-term financial instability.\n\nThe regulatory landscape for gig work is evolving rapidly. Some jurisdictions have enacted laws requiring platforms to provide minimum wage guarantees and benefits to workers. Others have maintained the independent contractor classification, preserving the flexibility that many workers value. The debate over how to balance flexibility with security is likely to continue as the gig economy grows and matures.",
"零工经济改变了全球数百万人的工作性质。零工经济以短期合同、自由职业和独立承包为特征，而非永久性就业，它既提供了灵活性也带来了不确定性。\n\n网约车司机、外卖送餐员、自由撰稿人和在线教师是参与零工经济的数百万人中的一部分。数字平台将这些工人与客户联系起来。\n\n然而，零工经济也有显著的缺点。工人通常缺乏健康保险、带薪休假和退休计划等福利。收入可能不可预测。\n\n零工工作的监管环境正在快速演变。一些司法管辖区已颁布法律要求平台为工人提供最低工资保障和福利。",
338,
[["What characterizes the gig economy?","Permanent employment with benefits","Short-term contracts, freelance work, and independent contracting","Government-assigned jobs","Only part-time retail work","B","文章指出零工经济以短期合同、自由职业和独立承包为特征。"],["What is the primary attraction of gig work for many workers?","High salaries","The flexibility to set their own hours and choose assignments","Guaranteed promotions","Company benefits","B","文章指出对许多人来说，设定自己的工作时间和选择任务的灵活性是主要吸引力。"],["What downside of gig work is mentioned?","Too much job security","Lack of benefits such as health insurance, paid leave, and retirement plans","Excessive vacation time","Too many promotions","B","文章指出零工工人通常缺乏健康保险、带薪休假和退休计划等福利。"],["The word 'downsides' most likely means:","Advantages","Disadvantages or negative aspects","Opportunities","Benefits","B","'downsides'意为'缺点、不利方面'。"]]],

  [71, "Sustainable Business Practices", "经济", 2,
"Sustainable business practices, once considered a niche concern, have moved into the mainstream of corporate strategy. Companies around the world are increasingly recognizing that environmental and social responsibility is not just an ethical obligation but also a competitive advantage.\n\nThe concept of the triple bottom line, which measures business performance in terms of people, planet, and profit, has gained widespread acceptance. Companies that prioritize sustainability can attract environmentally conscious consumers, reduce operational costs through energy efficiency, and mitigate risks associated with environmental regulations.\n\nCorporate sustainability reporting has become standard practice for large companies. Environmental, Social, and Governance criteria are increasingly used by investors to evaluate companies. Studies have shown that companies with strong ESG performance often deliver competitive financial returns over the long term.\n\nHowever, greenwashing remains a concern. Some companies exaggerate or fabricate their environmental credentials to appeal to conscious consumers without making meaningful changes to their practices. Independent verification and standardized reporting frameworks are helping to address this issue. Despite challenges, the trend toward sustainable business practices continues to accelerate, driven by consumer demand, regulatory pressure, and the recognition that sustainable practices are essential for long-term business success.",
"可持续商业实践曾经被视为小众关注，现在已进入企业战略的主流。全球各地的公司越来越认识到环境和社会责任不仅是道德义务，也是竞争优势。\n\n三重底线概念（人、地球和利润）已获得广泛接受。优先考虑可持续性的公司可以吸引环保意识消费者，通过节能降低运营成本。\n\n企业可持续发展报告已成为大公司的标准做法。环境、社会和治理标准被投资者越来越多地用来评估公司。\n\n然而，漂绿仍然是一个担忧。一些公司夸大或伪造其环保资质。独立验证和标准化报告框架正在帮助解决这个问题。",
338,
[["What is the triple bottom line?","Measuring only profit","Measuring business performance in terms of people, planet, and profit","Measuring only environmental impact","Measuring only employee satisfaction","B","文章指出三重底线从人、地球和利润三个方面衡量企业绩效。"],["What does ESG stand for?","Economic, Social, and Governmental","Environmental, Social, and Governance","Electronic, Scientific, and Global","Energy, Safety, and Growth","B","文章指出ESG代表环境、社会和治理。"],["What is greenwashing?","Using eco-friendly cleaning products","Exaggerating or fabricating environmental credentials without meaningful changes","Planting trees at corporate offices","Recycling office waste","B","文章指出漂绿是指夸大或伪造环保资质而不做实质性改变。"],["The word 'niche' most likely means:","Mainstream","Specialized and limited","Unimportant","Outdated","B","'niche'意为'小众的、专门的'。"]]],

  [72, "The Housing Crisis", "经济", 2,
"Housing affordability has become a crisis in many major cities around the world. As property prices and rents have soared far beyond wage growth, an increasing number of people are struggling to find adequate and affordable housing.\n\nThe causes of the housing crisis are complex and multifaceted. In many cities, restrictive zoning laws limit the construction of new housing, creating artificial scarcity. Speculative investment in real estate drives up prices, treating homes as financial assets rather than places to live. Construction costs have risen significantly, and the pace of new building has not kept up with population growth in many urban areas.\n\nThe consequences are severe. Young adults are increasingly unable to leave their parents' homes, delaying independence and family formation. Low-income families may spend more than half their income on rent, leaving little for other necessities. Homelessness is rising in many cities, with devastating effects on individuals and communities.\n\nSolutions include reforming zoning laws to allow more housing construction, implementing rent control or stabilization measures, increasing social housing investment, and taxing speculative property investment. Some cities are experimenting with innovative approaches such as community land trusts and cooperative housing models. Addressing the housing crisis requires coordinated action across government, private sector, and community organizations.",
"住房可负担性已成为全球许多主要城市的危机。随着房价和租金远远超过工资增长，越来越多的人难以找到适当和负担得起的住房。\n\n住房危机的原因是复杂多样的。在许多城市，限制性分区法规限制了新住房建设，造成了人为稀缺。房地产投机投资推高了价格。建筑成本显著上升。\n\n后果是严重的。年轻人越来越无法离开父母的家园。低收入家庭可能将一半以上的收入花在租金上。许多城市的无家可归者人数正在上升。\n\n解决方案包括改革分区法规、实施租金控制、增加社会住房投资和对投机性房地产投资征税。",
338,
[["What is a cause of the housing crisis?","Too much new housing construction","Restrictive zoning laws limiting new housing construction","Decreasing property prices","Too many vacant homes","B","文章指出限制性分区法规限制了新住房建设，造成人为稀缺。"],["What may low-income families spend on rent?","Less than 10% of income","About 25% of income","More than half their income","No rent at all","C","文章指出低收入家庭可能将一半以上收入花在租金上。"],["What is a community land trust?","A private golf course","A model where land is owned collectively to ensure long-term housing affordability","A type of bank","A government housing agency","B","文章提到社区土地信托是一种创新方法，旨在确保长期住房可负担性。"],["The word 'multifaceted' most likely means:","Simple and straightforward","Having many different aspects or causes","One-dimensional","Unimportant","B","'multifaceted'意为'多方面的、多层面的'。"]]],

  [73, "The Minimum Wage Debate", "经济", 2,
"The debate over minimum wage has intensified in recent years as income inequality has grown and the cost of living has risen. Advocates argue that higher minimum wages are necessary to ensure workers can meet their basic needs, while opponents contend that significant increases could lead to job losses and economic harm.\n\nProponents of raising the minimum wage point to the growing gap between productivity and wages. Since the 1970s, worker productivity has increased significantly, but the federal minimum wage in the United States has not kept pace with inflation. A full-time worker earning the federal minimum wage lives below the poverty line in most states.\n\nOpponents argue that significant minimum wage increases could force businesses to reduce hiring, cut hours, or automate jobs. Small businesses with thin profit margins may be particularly vulnerable. Some economists also warn that higher wages could lead to inflation as businesses pass increased labor costs on to consumers.\n\nResearch on the actual effects of minimum wage increases has produced mixed results. Some studies find minimal impact on employment, while others identify negative effects, particularly for young and low-skilled workers. Many cities and states have implemented higher minimum wages than the federal level, providing natural experiments for studying the effects. The debate continues as policymakers seek to balance the goal of fair wages with economic competitiveness.",
"随着收入不平等加剧和生活成本上升，最低工资辩论日益激烈。倡导者认为更高的最低工资对确保工人能够满足基本需求是必要的，而反对者则认为大幅增加可能导致失业和经济损害。\n\n提高最低工资的支持者指出生产率和工资之间日益增长的差距。自1970年代以来，工人生产率显著提高，但联邦最低工资未能跟上通胀。\n\n反对者认为大幅提高最低工资可能迫使企业减少招聘、削减工时或自动化工作。利润微薄的小企业可能特别脆弱。\n\n关于最低工资提高实际影响的研究结果不一。一些研究发现对就业影响极小，而另一些则确定了负面影响，特别是对年轻人和低技能工人。",
338,
[["What has happened to the gap between productivity and wages since the 1970s?","It has decreased","It has grown significantly","It has remained the same","It has disappeared","B","文章指出自1970年代以来生产率和工资之间的差距日益增长。"],["Where does a full-time worker earning the federal minimum wage live?","Above the poverty line","Below the poverty line in most states","In luxury","In the middle class","B","文章指出全职联邦最低工资工人在大多数州生活在贫困线以下。"],["What do opponents argue could result from significant minimum wage increases?","More hiring","Job losses, reduced hours, or automation","Lower prices","Increased profits","B","文章指出反对者认为大幅提高最低工资可能导致失业、削减工时或自动化。"],["What have studies on minimum wage effects found?","Consistent positive effects","Consistent negative effects","Mixed results","No effects at all","C","文章指出关于最低工资影响的研究结果不一。"]]],

  [74, "Intellectual Property in the Digital Age", "经济", 3,
"Intellectual property, including patents, copyrights, trademarks, and trade secrets, has become increasingly important in the knowledge-based economy. As digital technology makes it easier to copy and distribute creative works, protecting intellectual property rights while promoting innovation has become a complex challenge.\n\nCopyright protection in the digital age faces particular difficulties. Music, movies, books, and software can be copied and shared with millions of people at virtually no cost. While digital rights management technologies attempt to prevent unauthorized copying, they have had limited success. Streaming services have emerged as a legal and convenient alternative to piracy, though they provide significantly less revenue per unit to creators than traditional sales.\n\nPatent systems are also under strain. The number of patent applications has skyrocketed, and critics argue that many granted patents are overly broad or obvious, stifling rather than promoting innovation. Patent trolls, companies that acquire patents primarily to extract licensing fees through litigation, have become a significant problem.\n\nInternational intellectual property disputes have increased as the global economy becomes more interconnected. Developing countries argue that strict intellectual property protections favor wealthy nations and corporations, limiting access to essential medicines and technologies. Finding a balance that protects creators' rights while ensuring broad access to knowledge and innovation remains an ongoing challenge.",
"知识产权，包括专利、版权、商标和商业秘密，在知识经济中变得越来越重要。随着数字技术使复制和分发创意作品变得更加容易，在保护知识产权权利的同时促进创新已成为一个复杂的挑战。\n\n数字时代的版权保护面临特殊困难。音乐、电影、书籍和软件几乎可以零成本复制和分享给数百万人。流媒体服务已作为合法便捷的盗版替代方案出现。\n\n专利制度也面临压力。专利申请数量激增，批评者认为许多授予的专利过于宽泛或显而易见，反而扼杀而非促进创新。专利流氓已成为一个重大问题。\n\n国际知识产权争端随着全球经济更加互联而增加。发展中国家认为严格的知识产权保护偏袒富裕国家和公司。",
338,
[["What types of intellectual property are mentioned?","Only patents","Patents, copyrights, trademarks, and trade secrets","Only copyrights","Only trademarks","B","文章指出知识产权包括专利、版权、商标和商业秘密。"],["What are patent trolls?","Companies that invent new products","Companies that acquire patents primarily to extract licensing fees through litigation","Government patent offices","Inventors who file too many patents","B","文章指出专利流氓是主要为了通过诉讼获取许可费而获取专利的公司。"],["What have streaming services done?","Eliminated all piracy","Provided a legal and convenient alternative to piracy","Increased piracy","Made piracy easier","B","文章指出流媒体服务作为合法便捷的盗版替代方案出现。"],["What do developing countries argue about intellectual property?","Protections should be stronger","Strict protections favor wealthy nations and limit access to medicines and technologies","No intellectual property should exist","Only patents should be protected","B","文章指出发展中国家认为严格的知识产权保护偏袒富裕国家并限制获取药物和技术。"]]],

  [75, "The Future of Work", "经济", 2,
"The nature of work is undergoing a profound transformation driven by technological advancement, demographic shifts, and changing social expectations. Automation, artificial intelligence, and remote work are reshaping industries and redefining what it means to have a career.\n\nAutomation poses both opportunities and challenges. While it eliminates routine and dangerous tasks, it also threatens jobs in manufacturing, transportation, and administrative fields. Some estimates suggest that up to 30 percent of current jobs could be automated by 2030. However, history shows that technological change typically creates new types of jobs even as it eliminates others.\n\nRemote work, accelerated by the pandemic, has become a permanent fixture for many organizations. This shift offers benefits including reduced commuting time, greater geographic flexibility, and improved work-life balance. However, it also presents challenges such as social isolation, blurred boundaries between work and personal life, and reduced opportunities for spontaneous collaboration.\n\nThe skills required in the future workplace are evolving. Critical thinking, creativity, emotional intelligence, and adaptability are becoming more valuable than technical knowledge that can quickly become outdated. Lifelong learning and continuous skill development will be essential for workers to remain competitive in a rapidly changing labor market. Organizations and governments must invest in education and training programs to prepare the workforce for the jobs of tomorrow.",
"工作的性质正在经历由技术进步、人口结构变化和不断变化的社会期望驱动的深刻转变。自动化、人工智能和远程工作正在重塑行业。\n\n自动化既带来机遇也带来挑战。虽然它消除了常规和危险的任务，但也威胁着制造业、交通和行政领域的工作。一些估计表明到2030年多达30%的现有工作可能被自动化。\n\n由疫情加速的远程工作已成为许多组织的永久特征。这种转变提供了减少通勤时间、更大的地理灵活性和改善的工作与生活平衡等好处。\n\n未来工作场所所需的技能正在演变。批判性思维、创造力、情商和适应能力变得比可能很快过时的技术知识更有价值。",
338,
[["By 2030, what percentage of current jobs could potentially be automated?","Up to 10%","Up to 30%","Up to 60%","Up to 90%","B","文章指出到2030年多达30%的现有工作可能被自动化。"],["What benefit of remote work is mentioned?","More commuting time","Reduced commuting time and greater geographic flexibility","Less flexibility","More office space needed","B","文章指出远程工作提供减少通勤时间和更大的地理灵活性等好处。"],["What skills are becoming more valuable in the future workplace?","Routine repetitive skills","Critical thinking, creativity, emotional intelligence, and adaptability","Physical strength only","Memorization skills","B","文章指出批判性思维、创造力、情商和适应能力变得更有价值。"],["The word 'fixture' most likely means:","Temporary arrangement","A permanent or established feature","A broken item","A type of furniture","B","'fixture'意为'固定设施、永久特征'。"]]],

  [76, "Economic Impact of Aging Populations", "经济", 2,
"Many countries around the world are experiencing significant demographic shifts as their populations age. declining birth rates and increasing life expectancy are creating societies where older adults make up a growing proportion of the population, with profound economic implications.\n\nJapan is at the forefront of this trend, with nearly 30 percent of its population aged 65 or older. Many European countries and China face similar demographic trajectories. By 2050, the number of people aged 60 and above globally is expected to reach 2.1 billion, more than double the number in 2017.\n\nThe economic pressures of aging populations are substantial. Pension systems face mounting strain as fewer workers support more retirees. Healthcare costs rise disproportionately with age, putting pressure on public health budgets. Labor shortages may emerge as the working-age population shrinks, potentially slowing economic growth.\n\nHowever, aging populations also present opportunities. Older adults represent a growing consumer market for healthcare, leisure, and adapted products and services. Many older adults wish to remain active in the workforce, and their experience and skills can be valuable assets. Some countries are raising retirement ages, encouraging later-life employment, and investing in automation and productivity improvements to offset the economic effects of population aging.",
"许多国家正在经历人口老龄化的重要人口结构变化。出生率下降和预期寿命增加正在创造老年人占人口比例越来越大的社会。\n\n日本走在这一趋势的前列，近30%的人口年龄在65岁或以上。到2050年，全球60岁及以上人口预计将达到21亿。\n\n人口老龄化的经济压力是巨大的。养老金系统面临越来越大的压力。医疗保健费用随年龄不成比例地上升。随着劳动年龄人口减少，可能出现劳动力短缺。\n\n然而，老龄人口也带来了机遇。老年人代表了医疗保健、休闲和适应性产品服务的不断增长的消费市场。一些国家正在提高退休年龄、鼓励晚年就业和投资自动化。",
338,
[["What percentage of Japan's population is aged 65 or older?","About 15%","About 30%","About 45%","About 50%","B","文章指出日本近30%的人口年龄在65岁或以上。"],["By 2050, how many people aged 60 and above are expected globally?","About 1 billion","About 2.1 billion","About 5 billion","About 500 million","B","文章指出到2050年全球60岁及以上人口预计达到21亿。"],["What economic pressure do pension systems face?","Too much surplus funding","Mounting strain as fewer workers support more retirees","Decreasing number of retirees","Lower healthcare costs","B","文章指出养老金系统面临越来越大的压力，因为更少的工人支持更多的退休人员。"],["The word 'trajectories' most likely means:","Random events","Paths or courses of development","Accidents","Celebrations","B","'trajectories'意为'轨迹、发展路径'。"]]],

  [77, "The Role of Small Businesses", "经济", 1,
"Small businesses are often described as the backbone of the economy, and for good reason. In most countries, small and medium-sized enterprises account for the majority of businesses and a significant share of employment and economic output.\n\nGlobally, small and medium-sized enterprises represent about 90 percent of all businesses and provide more than 50 percent of employment. In the United States, small businesses have historically been responsible for creating roughly two-thirds of net new jobs. They bring innovation and competition to markets, often serving as testing grounds for new ideas and business models.\n\nHowever, small businesses face numerous challenges. Access to capital is frequently cited as a major obstacle, as small businesses may struggle to obtain loans from traditional banks. Regulatory compliance can be disproportionately burdensome for small operations that lack dedicated legal and accounting departments. Competition from large corporations and online retailers threatens many traditional small businesses.\n\nGovernment support for small businesses takes many forms, including loan guarantee programs, tax incentives, and procurement policies that favor small business suppliers. During the COVID-19 pandemic, many governments implemented emergency loan and grant programs to help small businesses survive the economic disruption. Supporting small businesses is widely recognized as essential for economic resilience and community vitality.",
"小企业常被称为经济的骨干。在大多数国家，中小企业占企业的多数，在就业和经济产出中占有重要份额。\n\n在全球范围内，中小企业约占所有企业的90%，提供50%以上的就业。在美国，小企业历史上创造了大约三分之二的新增就业岗位。\n\n然而，小企业面临许多挑战。获取资金常被视为主要障碍。法规合规对缺乏专门法律和会计部门的小企业来说可能负担过重。\n\n政府对小企业的支持有多种形式，包括贷款担保计划、税收优惠和偏好小企业供应商的采购政策。支持小企业被广泛认为对经济韧性和社区活力至关重要。",
338,
[["What percentage of all businesses do SMEs represent globally?","About 50%","About 70%","About 90%","About 99%","C","文章指出中小企业约占所有企业的90%。"],["What share of employment do SMEs provide globally?","About 20%","More than 50%","About 10%","About 75%","B","文章指出中小企业提供50%以上的就业。"],["In the US, what share of net new jobs have small businesses historically created?","About one-third","About two-thirds","About 90%","About 10%","B","文章指出美国小企业历史上创造了大约三分之二的新增就业岗位。"],["What is frequently cited as a major obstacle for small businesses?","Too many customers","Access to capital","Excessive profits","Too much government support","B","文章指出获取资金常被视为小企业的主要障碍。"]]],

  [78, "Financial Literacy", "经济", 1,
"Financial literacy, the ability to understand and effectively manage personal finances, is a critical skill in today's complex economic environment. Yet studies consistently show that financial literacy levels are alarmingly low worldwide, with significant consequences for individuals and economies.\n\nSurveys reveal that a large proportion of adults cannot answer basic financial questions about interest rates, inflation, and risk diversification. In the United States, only about one-third of adults can correctly answer basic financial literacy questions. The situation is similar or worse in many other countries.\n\nThe consequences of low financial literacy are far-reaching. Individuals who lack financial knowledge are more likely to accumulate excessive debt, fail to save for retirement, and fall victim to financial fraud. They may pay higher fees for financial products and make poor investment decisions. At the macroeconomic level, widespread financial illiteracy can contribute to financial instability.\n\nEfforts to improve financial literacy include incorporating personal finance education into school curricula, workplace financial wellness programs, and community-based financial education initiatives. Some countries have implemented national financial literacy strategies. However, research on the effectiveness of financial education programs has produced mixed results, suggesting that knowledge alone may not be sufficient to change financial behavior. Combining education with access to appropriate financial products and behavioral nudges may be more effective.",
"金融素养，即理解和管理个人财务的能力，是当今复杂经济环境中的关键技能。然而，研究一致表明全球金融素养水平低得令人担忧。\n\n调查显示很大一部分成年人无法回答关于利率、通胀和风险分散的基本金融问题。在美国，只有约三分之一的成年人能正确回答基本的金融素养问题。\n\n金融素养低下的后果是深远的。缺乏金融知识的人更可能积累过多债务、未能为退休储蓄和成为金融欺诈的受害者。\n\n提高金融素养的努力包括将个人理财教育纳入学校课程、工作场所金融健康计划和社区金融教育倡议。然而，关于金融教育计划有效性的研究产生了混合结果。",
338,
[["What percentage of US adults can correctly answer basic financial literacy questions?","About two-thirds","About one-third","About 90%","About 10%","B","文章指出美国只有约三分之一的成年人能正确回答基本金融素养问题。"],["What consequence of low financial literacy is mentioned?","Better investment decisions","Accumulating excessive debt and falling victim to fraud","Higher savings rates","Improved credit scores","B","文章指出金融素养低的人更可能积累过多债务和成为欺诈的受害者。"],["What approach to improving financial literacy may be more effective?","Education only","Combining education with access to financial products and behavioral nudges","Doing nothing","Only providing financial products","B","文章指出将教育与适当的金融产品和行为推动结合起来可能更有效。"],["The word 'nudges' most likely means:","Forcing people to do something","Gentle prompts or suggestions that influence behavior without restricting choice","Strict regulations","Financial penalties","B","'nudges'意为'助推'，指不限制选择的情况下影响行为的温和提示。"]]],

  [79, "The Economics of Climate Change", "经济", 3,
"The economic implications of climate change are vast and multifaceted, affecting virtually every sector of the global economy. From agricultural losses to infrastructure damage, the costs of inaction far exceed the costs of transitioning to a low-carbon economy.\n\nThe Stern Review, a landmark 2006 report on the economics of climate change, estimated that unmitigated climate change could reduce global GDP by 5 to 20 percent per year, while the costs of action to reduce greenhouse gas emissions could be limited to about 1 percent of global GDP per year. More recent analyses suggest that these cost estimates may have been conservative.\n\nThe transition to a low-carbon economy creates both risks and opportunities. Fossil fuel companies face the risk of stranded assets as the world shifts away from carbon-intensive energy. However, the clean energy sector is creating millions of jobs and attracting trillions of dollars in investment. Countries that lead in clean technology development stand to gain significant competitive advantages.\n\nCarbon pricing, through carbon taxes or cap-and-trade systems, is widely regarded by economists as the most efficient mechanism for reducing emissions. By putting a price on carbon, these policies incentivize businesses and consumers to reduce their carbon footprint. However, implementing carbon pricing faces political challenges, including concerns about competitiveness and the impact on low-income households. Revenue from carbon pricing can be used to offset these impacts through dividend payments or investment in clean energy.",
"气候变化的经济影响是巨大且多方面的，几乎影响全球经济的每个部门。从农业损失到基础设施损坏，不采取行动的成本远超过向低碳经济转型的成本。\n\n2006年的斯特恩报告估计，未减缓的气候变化可能每年使全球GDP减少5%到20%，而减少温室气体排放的行动成本可以限制在每年约1%的全球GDP。\n\n向低碳经济转型既带来风险也带来机遇。化石燃料公司面临资产搁浅的风险。然而，清洁能源部门正在创造数百万就业岗位并吸引数万亿投资。\n\n碳定价，通过碳税或总量控制与交易系统，被经济学家广泛认为是减少排放的最有效机制。然而，实施碳定价面临政治挑战。",
338,
[["According to the Stern Review, by how much could unmitigated climate change reduce global GDP?","1 to 2 percent per year","5 to 20 percent per year","30 to 50 percent per year","100 percent per year","B","文章指出未减缓的气候变化可能每年使全球GDP减少5%到20%。"],["What is the estimated cost of action to reduce greenhouse gas emissions?","About 10% of global GDP per year","About 1% of global GDP per year","About 5% of global GDP per year","About 20% of global GDP per year","B","文章指出减少排放的行动成本约为每年1%的全球GDP。"],["What is carbon pricing?","Making carbon products free","Putting a price on carbon through taxes or cap-and-trade systems","Eliminating all carbon","Increasing carbon emissions","B","文章指出碳定价是通过碳税或总量控制与交易系统为碳定价。"],["The word 'stranded' in 'stranded assets' most likely means:","Well-invested","Assets that have suffered an unanticipated write-down or become worthless","Floating","Newly discovered","B","'stranded assets'意为'搁浅资产'，指因市场变化而贬值或变得无价值的资产。"]]],

  [80, "The Rise of Fintech", "经济", 2,
"Financial technology, commonly known as fintech, is transforming the financial services industry at an unprecedented pace. From mobile payments to robo-advisors, fintech innovations are changing how people save, invest, borrow, and transact.\n\nMobile payment systems have seen explosive growth, particularly in developing countries. In China, mobile payment platforms like Alipay and WeChat Pay have largely replaced cash for everyday transactions. In Africa, M-Pesa has brought financial services to millions of previously unbanked people. These platforms offer convenience and accessibility that traditional banking systems have struggled to provide.\n\nRobo-advisors use algorithms to provide automated investment management services at a fraction of the cost of traditional financial advisors. This has democratized access to investment management, allowing people with smaller portfolios to benefit from professional investment strategies.\n\nPeer-to-peer lending platforms connect borrowers directly with lenders, bypassing traditional banks and potentially offering better rates for both parties. Crowdfunding platforms have opened new avenues for startups and creative projects to raise capital.\n\nHowever, fintech also raises regulatory concerns. Consumer protection, data privacy, and financial stability are all areas where regulatory frameworks are struggling to keep pace with innovation. Finding the right balance between fostering innovation and protecting consumers remains a key challenge for regulators worldwide.",
"金融科技正以前所未有的速度改变金融服务业。从移动支付到机器人顾问，金融科技创新正在改变人们储蓄、投资、借贷和交易的方式。\n\n移动支付系统出现了爆炸性增长，特别是在发展中国家。在中国，支付宝和微信支付等移动支付平台已在日常交易中基本取代了现金。在非洲，M-Pesa为数百万以前没有银行服务的人带来了金融服务。\n\n机器人顾问使用算法以传统金融顾问成本的一小部分提供自动化投资管理服务。\n\n点对点借贷平台将借款人直接与出借人连接起来，绕过传统银行。众筹平台为初创企业和创意项目开辟了筹集资本的新途径。\n\n然而，金融科技也引发了监管担忧。消费者保护、数据隐私和金融稳定都是监管框架难以跟上创新的领域。",
338,
[["What has largely replaced cash for everyday transactions in China?","Credit cards","Mobile payment platforms like Alipay and WeChat Pay","Checks","Bartering","B","文章指出中国支付宝和微信支付等移动支付平台已在日常交易中基本取代了现金。"],["What do robo-advisors use to provide investment services?","Human financial advisors","Algorithms for automated investment management","Crystal balls","Random selection","B","文章指出机器人顾问使用算法提供自动化投资管理服务。"],["What has M-Pesa done in Africa?","Only provided internet access","Brought financial services to millions of previously unbanked people","Created a new cryptocurrency","Built physical banks","B","文章指出M-Pesa为数百万以前没有银行服务的人带来了金融服务。"],["The word 'democratized' most likely means in this context:","Made available to everyone, not just the wealthy","Made political","Made expensive","Made secret","A","'democratized'意为'民主化'，即让服务对所有人开放。"]]],

  [81, "Trade Wars and Their Impact", "经济", 2,
"Trade wars, characterized by escalating tariffs and trade barriers between countries, have become a significant feature of the global economic landscape. When countries impose tariffs on each other's goods, the consequences can ripple through the entire global economy.\n\nThe United States and China have been at the center of recent trade tensions. Beginning in 2018, the two countries imposed tariffs on hundreds of billions of dollars worth of goods. The stated goals were to reduce trade deficits and protect domestic industries from unfair competition. However, the actual effects were more complex than intended.\n\nStudies have shown that the costs of tariffs are primarily borne by domestic consumers and businesses, not by foreign exporters. When tariffs raise the price of imported goods, consumers pay more at the store. Businesses that rely on imported materials face higher production costs, which can reduce competitiveness and lead to job losses.\n\nAgricultural sectors have been particularly hard hit by trade wars, as affected countries often target agricultural exports in retaliation. Farmers who lost access to major markets faced financial hardship, and government subsidy programs to offset these losses added to fiscal burdens. While some industries may benefit from reduced foreign competition, the overall economic impact of trade wars tends to be negative, reducing economic growth and increasing uncertainty.",
"贸易战，以国家之间升级的关税和贸易壁垒为特征，已成为全球经济格局的重要特征。\n\n美国和中国一直处于近期贸易紧张局势的中心。从2018年开始，两国对价值数千亿美元的商品征收关税。\n\n研究表明，关税的成本主要由国内消费者和企业承担，而非外国出口商。当关税提高进口商品的价格时，消费者在商店支付更多。\n\n农业部门受贸易战打击尤其严重，因为受影响的国家通常以农业出口作为报复目标。虽然某些行业可能从减少外国竞争中受益，但贸易战的总体经济影响倾向于负面。",
338,
[["When did US-China trade tensions escalate significantly?","2010","2015","2018","2022","C","文章指出从2018年开始美中贸易紧张局势升级。"],["Who primarily bears the costs of tariffs according to studies?","Foreign exporters","Domestic consumers and businesses","Only the government","Only foreign governments","B","文章指出关税成本主要由国内消费者和企业承担。"],["Which sector has been particularly hard hit by trade wars?","Technology","Agriculture","Mining","Tourism","B","文章指出农业部门受贸易战打击尤其严重。"],["The word 'retaliation' most likely means:","Cooperation","Counter-attack or revenge","Negotiation","Celebration","B","'retaliation'意为'报复'。"]]],

  [82, "The Economics of Healthcare", "经济", 2,
"Healthcare spending continues to rise around the world, posing significant challenges for governments, businesses, and individuals. In the United States, healthcare spending accounts for approximately 18 percent of GDP, far more than any other developed country, yet health outcomes are not proportionally better.\n\nThe reasons for rising healthcare costs are complex. An aging population requires more medical care. Advances in medical technology, while improving outcomes, often come at high prices. Administrative costs are substantial, particularly in countries with complex insurance systems. The prevalence of chronic diseases such as diabetes and heart disease also contributes to spending growth.\n\nDifferent countries have adopted different approaches to healthcare financing. Some, like the United Kingdom, have single-payer systems funded through taxation that provide universal coverage. Others, like the United States, rely on a mix of private insurance and government programs. Each system has trade-offs between cost, access, and quality.\n\nThe debate over healthcare reform often centers on the role of government versus the private sector. Proponents of government-funded systems argue that they provide more equitable access and lower administrative costs. Supporters of market-based approaches contend that competition drives innovation and efficiency. Finding sustainable solutions that balance cost control with quality and access remains one of the most pressing policy challenges worldwide.",
"全球医疗保健支出持续上升，对政府、企业和个人构成了重大挑战。在美国，医疗保健支出约占GDP的18%，远超任何其他发达国家，但健康结果并不成比例地更好。\n\n医疗成本上升的原因是复杂的。人口老龄化需要更多医疗护理。医疗技术的进步虽然改善了结果，但往往价格高昂。行政成本巨大。\n\n不同国家采用了不同的医疗融资方式。一些国家如英国拥有通过税收资助的单一支付者系统，提供全民覆盖。其他国家如美国则依赖私人保险和政府计划的混合。\n\n医疗改革的辩论通常围绕政府与私营部门的角色展开。寻找在成本控制与质量和获取之间取得平衡的可持续解决方案仍然是全球最紧迫的政策挑战之一。",
338,
[["What percentage of GDP does US healthcare spending account for?","About 8%","About 12%","About 18%","About 25%","C","文章指出美国医疗保健支出约占GDP的18%。"],["What system does the UK have for healthcare?","A purely private system","A single-payer system funded through taxation providing universal coverage","No healthcare system","Only emergency care","B","文章指出英国拥有通过税收资助的单一支付者系统，提供全民覆盖。"],["What contributes to rising healthcare costs?","Only aging populations","Aging populations, expensive medical technology, administrative costs, and chronic diseases","Only technology costs","Only administrative costs","B","文章指出多种因素包括人口老龄化、昂贵的医疗技术、行政成本和慢性疾病。"],["The word 'trade-offs' most likely means:","Perfect solutions","Compromises where one thing is given up for another","Financial profits","Simple choices","B","'trade-offs'意为'权衡'，指为了获得某物而放弃另一物的妥协。"]]],

  [83, "Consumer Behavior and Marketing", "经济", 1,
"Understanding consumer behavior is essential for businesses seeking to market their products effectively. Consumer decisions are influenced by a complex interplay of psychological, social, cultural, and economic factors that marketers must understand to succeed.\n\nPsychological factors include perception, motivation, learning, and attitudes. Consumers may not be fully aware of the subconscious factors that influence their purchasing decisions. For example, the placement of products in a store, the colors used in packaging, and the music playing in the background can all affect buying behavior without the consumer realizing it.\n\nSocial factors are equally important. Family, friends, and social groups all influence what products people buy. The rise of social media has amplified this effect, with influencers and online reviews shaping consumer preferences at an unprecedented scale. Consumers often make purchasing decisions based on what they perceive others are doing or approving of.\n\nDigital marketing has transformed how companies reach consumers. Targeted advertising uses data about consumers' online behavior to deliver personalized messages. While this can make marketing more relevant, it also raises privacy concerns. The use of psychological principles in marketing, sometimes called neuromarketing, has sparked debate about the ethics of manipulating consumer behavior.",
"理解消费者行为对于有效营销产品的企业至关重要。消费者决策受到心理、社会、文化和经济因素复杂相互作用的影响。\n\n心理因素包括感知、动机、学习和态度。消费者可能不完全意识到影响其购买决策的潜意识因素。例如，产品在商店中的位置、包装使用的颜色和背景播放的音乐都可能影响购买行为。\n\n社会因素同样重要。家人、朋友和社会群体都影响人们购买什么产品。社交媒体的兴起放大了这种效应。\n\n数字营销改变了公司接触消费者的方式。定向广告使用消费者在线行为数据来传递个性化信息。虽然这可以使营销更相关，但也引发了隐私担忧。",
338,
[["What factors influence consumer decisions?","Only price","A complex interplay of psychological, social, cultural, and economic factors","Only advertising","Only product quality","B","文章指出消费者决策受到心理、社会、文化和经济因素复杂相互作用的影响。"],["What can affect buying behavior without the consumer realizing it?","Only the price","Product placement, packaging colors, and background music","Only the brand name","Only the product quality","B","文章指出产品位置、包装颜色和背景音乐可能在消费者不知不觉中影响购买行为。"],["What has amplified the social influence on consumer behavior?","Reduced internet access","The rise of social media and online reviews","Decreased advertising","Fewer products available","B","文章指出社交媒体的兴起和在线评论放大了社会对消费者行为的影响。"],["What is neuromarketing?","Marketing to neurologists","The use of psychological principles in marketing","Marketing without any technology","A type of brain surgery","B","文章指出神经营销学是在营销中使用心理原则。"]]],

  [84, "The Impact of Automation on Jobs", "经济", 2,
"Automation has been reshaping the labor market for centuries, from the Industrial Revolution's mechanization of textile production to today's artificial intelligence-powered systems. While automation has consistently increased productivity and living standards, it has also displaced workers and transformed the nature of employment.\n\nThe current wave of automation differs from previous ones in both scale and scope. Artificial intelligence and robotics are now capable of performing tasks that were once thought to require human judgment and creativity. This means that automation is no longer limited to routine manual labor but increasingly affects professional and knowledge-based occupations.\n\nThe economic effects of automation are complex. Productivity gains from automation can increase overall economic output and create new types of jobs. However, the transition can be painful for displaced workers, particularly those whose skills are closely tied to automated tasks. Geographic and demographic disparities can mean that the benefits and costs of automation are unevenly distributed.\n\nPreparing for an automated future requires significant investment in education and retraining programs. Workers need to develop skills that complement rather than compete with automation, such as creative problem-solving, emotional intelligence, and complex communication. Social safety nets may need to be strengthened to support workers during transitions. Some economists have even proposed universal basic income as a response to potential large-scale job displacement.",
"自动化几个世纪以来一直在重塑劳动力市场。虽然自动化持续提高了生产力和生活水平，但也取代了工人并改变了就业性质。\n\n当前的自动化浪潮在规模和范围上都不同于以往。人工智能和机器人现在能够执行曾被认为是需要人类判断和创造力的任务。\n\n自动化的经济影响是复杂的。自动化带来的生产力提高可以增加整体经济产出并创造新类型的就业。然而，对被取代的工人来说，过渡可能是痛苦的。\n\n为自动化未来做准备需要在教育和再培训计划方面进行大量投资。工人需要发展与自动化互补而非竞争的技能。一些经济学家甚至提出了全民基本收入作为对潜在大规模失业的回应。",
338,
[["How does the current wave of automation differ from previous ones?","It is smaller in scale","It affects professional and knowledge-based occupations, not just manual labor","It only affects manufacturing","It has no economic impact","B","文章指出当前自动化不再仅限于常规体力劳动，而是越来越多地影响专业和知识型职业。"],["What skills should workers develop to complement automation?","Routine repetitive skills","Creative problem-solving, emotional intelligence, and complex communication","Only technical skills","Only physical strength","B","文章指出工人需要发展与自动化互补的技能，如创造性解决问题、情商和复杂沟通。"],["What has been proposed as a response to potential large-scale job displacement?","Eliminating all technology","Universal basic income","Reducing education","Increasing manual labor","B","文章指出一些经济学家提出了全民基本收入作为回应。"],["The word 'displaced' most likely means:","Promoted","Having one's job or position taken away","Happily employed","Relocated to a better position","B","'displaced'意为'被取代的、被解雇的'。"]]]
];
